\begin{abstract}
RetailPulse is a Databricks-first retail analytics project built around a validated Instacart implementation. The project takes grocery order history through a bronze, silver, and gold Delta Lake pipeline, persists OLAP and report tables, derives cross-sell recommendations and customer segments, validates a replay-style streaming flow, and publishes a five-page Databricks AI/BI dashboard for review. This report documents the submission-safe version of the system validated on April 5, 2026 through Databricks job \texttt{61936309152043} and successful run \texttt{631388168060027}. The report intentionally stays honest about the source data and platform: the Instacart dataset does not contain raw prices or absolute calendar dates, the current workspace target is Databricks Free Edition serverless, and the classifier and regression outputs remain exploratory rather than operational proof. Within those constraints, RetailPulse demonstrates a coherent warehouse-style analytics system with reproducible orchestration, reusable report tables, clear evidence packaging, and a dashboard surface aligned with the notebook pipeline.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Databricks, Delta Lake, retail analytics, Instacart, medallion architecture, association rules, clustering, streaming validation, dashboarding.
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section*{1. Problem Statement}
Retail analytics projects often fail in one of two ways. They either stop at raw exploratory notebooks with no reproducible data model, or they overclaim business insight from weakly packaged analytics that cannot be rerun, validated, or reviewed by another engineer. The goal of RetailPulse was to avoid both failures by building a small but defensible retail analytics system around public grocery order history. The system needed to ingest data into Databricks, standardize it into a lakehouse pipeline, expose warehouse-style analytics outputs, demonstrate recommendation and segmentation capabilities, validate its own outputs, and present the results through a dashboard and evidence pack instead of isolated notebook screenshots.

The project scope was intentionally grounded in the actual capabilities of the Instacart dataset and the target platform. Instacart is well suited to basket analytics, reorder behavior, association rules, and customer segmentation because it provides order-item level history with user, product, aisle, and department information. However, it does not provide raw prices or absolute dates, so the system could not honestly claim revenue analytics or month-over-month sales reporting. Likewise, Databricks Free Edition serverless is capable enough to support Delta pipelines, SQL analytics, Structured Streaming with \texttt{AvailableNow}, and AI/BI dashboards, but it imposes practical limits that require conservative implementation choices \cite{databricks_free, databricks_streaming}. RetailPulse therefore frames the problem as grocery order analytics and recommendation on Databricks, not as a full production commerce platform.

The final problem statement can be expressed in operational terms: given public order-item data, build a reproducible Databricks workflow that transforms raw CSVs into validated analytics tables, produces reviewable descriptive and exploratory outputs, and presents them through a consistent dashboard and report-pack story. The report evaluates whether that goal was met using the repo-tracked workflow, the persisted tables, the screenshot pack, and the validated live run metadata.

\subsection*{1.5 Why Databricks?}
Databricks was chosen because the project needed one surface that could support ingestion, transformation, storage, analytics, orchestration, and presentation without forcing the submission into disconnected tools. Delta tables and Unity Catalog volumes provide a straightforward way to structure the bronze, silver, and gold layers. Databricks Asset Bundles provide a reproducible deployment model for the notebook workflow. Databricks SQL and AI/BI dashboards provide a reviewer-friendly output surface that is stronger than asking an evaluator to inspect raw notebooks. These capabilities make Databricks a good fit for a course project whose value depends not only on algorithms, but also on packaging, repeatability, and clarity \cite{delta_medallion, databricks_bundles, databricks_dashboards}.

Databricks also imposed design discipline. Because the target environment was Free Edition serverless, the project had to avoid assumptions that only work on larger or stateful clusters. This directly influenced several implementation decisions: sampling is done locally rather than by fetching Kaggle data in notebooks; recommendation mining uses a serverless-safe pairwise approach rather than FP-growth; streaming validation uses \texttt{Trigger.AvailableNow}; and the final performance section documents that \texttt{OPTIMIZE} did not improve the benchmark queries on the small sample. These constraints helped keep the final project honest and reproducible rather than artificially polished.

