At the live-workspace level, the validated run facts are themselves deliverables because they prove that the packaged workflow was executed end to end. The authoritative release record lists Databricks job \texttt{61936309152043}, successful run \texttt{631388168060027}, the published dashboard \texttt{RetailPulse Demo Dashboard}, and dashboard revision timestamp \texttt{2026-04-05T08:40:02.619Z}. The report therefore evaluates a concrete implemented state rather than a planned architecture.

The deliverables also include a strict narrative structure. Dashboard V2 and the report-pack notebook share the same five reviewer-facing sections: Executive Overview, Order Behavior, Recommendations and Segments, Execution and Data Quality, Experimental Insights and Performance. This matters because it keeps the report, the dashboard, the notebook fallback, and the screenshot evidence synchronized instead of forcing the reviewer to reconstruct the story from mismatched surfaces.

\section*{3. Dataset and Why We Picked That Dataset}
RetailPulse uses the public Instacart order-history dataset as its source data \cite{instacart}. This dataset was selected because it offers the right grain for a retail analytics capstone: user-level order sequences, order-item line data, product information, aisles, and departments. Those characteristics support the main analytical questions targeted by the project: Which product combinations recur in baskets? Which customer groups behave similarly? What departments dominate demand by day and hour? How can a warehouse-style data model summarize order behavior cleanly?

The project does not use the entire source dataset directly inside Databricks. Instead, it creates a deterministic \(10\%\) sample locally by keeping users that satisfy the configured sampling rule and then filtering the order-product files to the corresponding \texttt{order\_id} set. That smaller sample is more manageable for Free Edition quotas while remaining large enough to produce meaningful association rules, segments, and report tables. The validated sample sizes are shown in Table~\ref{tab:samplecounts}.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Deterministic Instacart sample used by RetailPulse.}
\label{tab:samplecounts}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lr}
\toprule
\textbf{Sample file} & \textbf{Rows} \\
\midrule
\texttt{orders.csv} & 341,974 \\
\texttt{order\_products\_\_prior.csv} & 3,267,191 \\
\texttt{order\_products\_\_train.csv} & 137,847 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The choice of Instacart was driven by analytic fit rather than convenience alone. Many public retail datasets either lack order-item detail or are too synthetic to support realistic behavior analysis. Instacart preserves the transaction grain needed for medallion modeling, association-rule mining, and customer-feature engineering. It also supports a strong star-schema design because the data naturally separates into orders, users, products, aisles, and departments.

At the same time, the dataset imposes non-negotiable limitations, and those limitations directly shape the report. Instacart does not include raw product prices or revenue, so RetailPulse focuses on item counts, basket size, reorder rate, day-of-week, hour-of-day, and days-since-prior-order. It also does not provide absolute calendar dates, so the project uses \texttt{order\_dow}, \texttt{order\_hour\_of\_day}, and \texttt{days\_since\_prior\_order} rather than fabricated month or year dimensions. This is why the system should be described as grocery order analytics and recommendation, not as sales or calendar analytics.

