\label{fig:streamopt}
\end{figure*}

The execution-quality layer is one of the strongest parts of the project. The streaming replay notebook checked 158 order-slot groups and found 0 mismatches between the streaming aggregate and the equivalent batch calculation. Likewise, the OLAP notebook persisted a validation table that compares cube totals with direct fact-table totals. These checks matter because they turn the data-quality story into explicit evidence rather than a visual claim.

The optimization benchmark is another example of honest reporting. The project ran \texttt{OPTIMIZE} and \texttt{ZORDER BY} correctly, persisted raw timings and a summary table, and then documented that the measured queries became slower on this small sample. For \texttt{department\_hour\_distribution}, the runtime changed from 0.6994 seconds to 0.8350 seconds. For \texttt{user\_basket\_summary}, the runtime changed from 0.6828 seconds to 0.9789 seconds. This is not a failure of the report; it is evidence that the report does not hide inconvenient outcomes.

