Finally, the report retains the exploratory supervised-model outputs while keeping them in the correct lane. The decision tree achieved accuracy 0.9136 and AUC 0.8813 against a majority-baseline accuracy of 0.7445, while the linear regression achieved RMSE 5.0945 and \(R^2 = 0.5580\) against a mean-baseline RMSE of 7.6627. These metrics are useful for discussion and dashboard completeness, but they are not the primary proof points of the system because the feature design still needs a stricter leakage-safe redesign.
\section*{6. Detailed Explanation of Each Notebook, Its Working, and Code}
The notebook workflow is the backbone of RetailPulse. Each notebook has one bounded responsibility and writes outputs that become the inputs for the next stage. This keeps the pipeline linear and inspectable.

\subsection*{6.1 Environment and ingestion notebooks}
\textbf{Notebook 00 -- \texttt{00\_setup.py}.} This notebook initializes the working environment inside Databricks. It accepts widgets for \texttt{catalog}, \texttt{schema}, \texttt{raw\_volume}, \texttt{replay\_volume}, and \texttt{checkpoint\_volume}. Its core job is to create the schema if needed, switch the SQL context, and create the Unity Catalog volumes that later stages depend on. The notebook also surfaces the resolved paths so the operator knows exactly where raw files, replay batches, and checkpoints should live.

\begin{verbatim}
spark.sql(f"CREATE SCHEMA IF NOT EXISTS {qname(catalog, schema)}")
for volume in (raw_volume, replay_volume, checkpoint_volume):
    spark.sql(f"CREATE VOLUME IF NOT EXISTS {qname(catalog, schema, volume)}")
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Notebook 01 -- \texttt{01\_sample\_and\_upload.py}.} This notebook does not perform sampling itself. Sampling happens locally for portability and to stay within serverless constraints. The notebook instead validates that the expected CSV files were uploaded to the raw volume and computes preview row counts. This is a good example of explicit pipeline discipline: the project does not silently proceed if the raw upload contract is incomplete.

\textbf{Notebook 02 -- \texttt{02\_bronze\_ingest.py}.} This notebook ingests the uploaded CSVs into explicit-schema Delta tables. It defines the schemas for orders, order-product rows, products, aisles, and departments; reads the CSVs from the raw volume; asserts that each frame is non-empty; and then writes the bronze tables with overwrite-schema enabled. The explicit-schema step is important because it prevents accidental type drift in the rest of the pipeline.

\begin{verbatim}
bronze_frames = {
    "bronze_orders": read_csv("orders.csv", orders_schema),
    "bronze_order_products_prior": read_csv("order_products__prior.csv",
                                           order_products_schema),
    ...
}
\end{verbatim}

\subsection*{6.2 Cleansing and warehouse-model notebooks}
\textbf{Notebook 03 -- \texttt{03\_silver\_transform.py}.} This notebook standardizes types, removes obvious bad keys, enriches products with aisle and department attributes, unions prior and train order-item sets, and creates reusable user-history aggregates. The key outputs are \texttt{silver\_orders}, \texttt{silver\_order\_items}, \texttt{silver\_products\_enriched}, and \texttt{silver\_user\_history}. Its role is to move the data from raw landing format into a cleaned analytical shape.

\textbf{Notebook 04 -- \texttt{04\_gold\_model.py}.} This notebook creates the star-schema tables and the user-feature mart used downstream. It generates dimensions for users, products, aisles, departments, and order slots; facts for order items and orders; and the \texttt{mart\_user\_features} table used by clustering and the exploratory ML notebooks. It also runs basic contract checks, such as null-key counts and whether \texttt{reordered} values stay in the expected 0/1 range.

\begin{verbatim}
fact_orders = (
    fact_order_items.groupBy("order_id", "user_id", "eval_set",
                             "order_number", "order_dow",
                             "order_hour_of_day", "days_since_prior_order")
    .agg(F.count("*").alias("basket_size"),
         F.sum("reordered").alias("reordered_item_count"),
         F.countDistinct("department_id").alias("distinct_department_count"))
)
\end{verbatim}

\subsection*{6.3 Analytics notebooks}
\textbf{Notebook 05 -- \texttt{05\_olap.py}.} This notebook performs the descriptive warehouse analysis. It executes a \texttt{CUBE} over department and day-of-week, a \texttt{ROLLUP} over day-of-week and hour, and a basket-size analysis by daypart and department. It also computes a validation table by comparing cube totals against manually grouped fact totals. The persisted outputs are \texttt{report\_olap\_cube}, \texttt{report\_olap\_rollup}, \texttt{report\_olap\_basket}, and \texttt{report\_olap\_validation}. The underlying aggregation pattern follows standard Spark SQL grouping analytics \cite{spark_sql}.

\textbf{Notebook 06 -- \texttt{06\_association\_rules.py}.} This notebook derives pairwise association rules from order baskets. It accepts widget-configured \texttt{min\_support}, \texttt{min\_confidence}, and \texttt{seed\_products}. It first collects the unique products per order, explodes the basket into item pairs, computes antecedent and consequent counts, and then derives support, confidence, and lift. The rules are written to \texttt{mart\_association\_rules}. A second cell then demonstrates how to retrieve recommendation candidates for one or more seed products.

\begin{verbatim}
baskets = fact_order_items.groupBy("order_id") \
    .agg(F.collect_set("product_id").alias("items")) \
    .filter(F.size("items") >= 2)
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Notebook 07 -- \texttt{07\_clustering.py}.} This notebook clusters customers using KMeans over the engineered user features. It standardizes the feature vector, evaluates \(k = 3, 4, 5\) with silhouette score, persists the model-selection summary to \texttt{report\_cluster\_k\_scores}, writes the chosen \texttt{cluster\_id} back into \texttt{mart\_user\_features}, and then materializes cluster profiles in \texttt{report\_cluster\_profiles}. Its role is not just segmentation, but also creating reusable segment context for the dashboard. The clustering, classifier, and regression notebooks all use the Spark ML DataFrame-based APIs \cite{spark_ml}.

\subsection*{6.4 Exploratory predictive notebooks}
\textbf{Notebook 08 -- \texttt{08\_classifier.py}.} This notebook trains a \texttt{DecisionTreeClassifier} to predict whether a user belongs to the top quartile of \texttt{total\_orders}. It uses feature columns such as basket size, reorder behavior, active days, and \texttt{cluster\_id}. The notebook computes AUC, accuracy, a majority-class baseline, and the threshold value used to define \texttt{power\_user}. It then writes \texttt{report\_classifier\_metrics} and \texttt{report\_classifier\_feature\_importance}. The code is straightforward and reproducible, but the report explicitly treats the outcome as exploratory because of leakage risk in the feature design.

\textbf{Notebook 09 -- \texttt{09\_regression.py}.} This notebook trains a \texttt{LinearRegression} model to predict \texttt{basket\_size} from order context and user-level history. It joins \texttt{fact\_orders} with the user-feature mart, assembles the model vector, performs a train/test split, and persists RMSE, \(R^2\), and the mean-baseline RMSE to \texttt{report\_regression\_metrics}. Like the classifier notebook, it is included because it demonstrates a predictive analytics lane, but the report avoids presenting it as operationally rigorous.

\subsection*{6.5 Validation and performance notebooks}
\textbf{Notebook 10 -- \texttt{10\_streaming\_replay.py}.} This notebook demonstrates a replay-style Structured Streaming flow that is compatible with Databricks Free Edition serverless. It creates a held-out slice of orders, partitions them into a small number of CSV batches, writes them to a replay volume, reads them back using \texttt{readStream}, aggregates them by day and hour, and writes the results to \texttt{stream\_order\_slot\_metrics} using \texttt{availableNow=True}. It then compares the streaming aggregate with an equivalent batch aggregate and persists the comparison in \texttt{report\_stream\_validation}. The final assertion that mismatches equal zero is one of the strongest pieces of correctness evidence in the project.

\begin{verbatim}
query = (
    stream_metrics.writeStream.format("delta")
    .outputMode("complete")
    .option("checkpointLocation", checkpoint_root)
    .trigger(availableNow=True)
    .toTable(qname("stream_order_slot_metrics"))
)
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Notebook 11 -- \texttt{11\_optimize.py}.} This notebook benchmarks two representative queries before and after \texttt{OPTIMIZE ... ZORDER BY}. It measures runtime by collecting the query result, writes raw timing rows to \texttt{report\_optimize\_timings}, and writes a pivoted summary table to \texttt{report\_optimize\_summary}. The notebook is important because it demonstrates physical-table optimization and performance measurement without pretending that optimization must always help on small datasets.

\subsection*{6.6 Presentation notebook}
\textbf{Notebook 12 -- \texttt{12\_report\_pack.py}.} This notebook is the final evidence hub. It mirrors Dashboard V2 with the same five sections and collects the key report tables into one notebook surface. It computes table counts, order-by-day summaries, top products, recommendation rules, seed recommendations, segment profiles, OLAP validation summaries, stream validation detail, exploratory model metrics, feature importance, and optimize timing views. When the dashboard is unavailable, this notebook becomes the canonical fallback presentation surface.

In aggregate, the notebook design follows a strong submission pattern: each notebook has one responsibility, downstream steps consume persisted tables rather than hidden notebook state, and the final report-facing evidence is stored in reusable report tables. That is a stronger engineering posture than a typical notebook chain built around temporary views and manual screenshots.

\section*{7. Limitations and Lessons Learned}
RetailPulse is strongest when it stays honest about its boundaries. The first limitation is the source data. Instacart does not contain raw prices or absolute dates, so any claim about revenue trends, profit, or month-over-month seasonality would be unsupported. The system therefore uses relative order timing and item-level counts instead of inventing facts that are not present in the data.

The second limitation is the platform target. Databricks Free Edition serverless is good enough for a capstone-quality implementation, but it is not a final production environment. It shaped the recommendation path, the streaming implementation, and the operational release posture. The project learned to favor reliability and portability over algorithmic ambition in a few places. For example, pairwise association rules replaced FP-growth because they were more dependable in the serverless setting.

The third limitation is methodological. The classifier and regression outputs are informative, but the feature pipelines are not yet submission-rigorous enough to support strong predictive claims. The clustering path includes \texttt{total\_orders} in its feature set, and the classifier later uses \texttt{cluster\_id} while predicting a label derived from \texttt{total\_orders}. The regression path joins user aggregates back into per-order prediction without a strict temporal boundary. The lesson is that predictive metrics can be attractive and still need to be demoted to exploratory status if the feature design is not leakage-safe.

The fourth lesson is about evidence packaging. Early versions of the project were stronger on implementation than on proof discipline. The final release improved this by persisting OLAP outputs, adding validation tables, publishing the dashboard, and standardizing the screenshot pack. That change is not cosmetic; it materially improves the credibility of the submission.
\section*{8. Future Work}
The next major step for RetailPulse is to evolve from an Instacart-specific internal pilot into a multi-dataset self-service analytics system. The planned architecture keeps Databricks as the backend and system of record, but introduces a Streamlit-based Databricks App for upload, file-role assignment, column mapping, validation, run submission, and artifact download. In that model, each uploaded dataset receives a \texttt{dataset\_id}, a stored mapping manifest, and a controlled processing lifecycle.

The pipeline itself would need to become dataset-aware. Instead of overwriting single-dataset tables, the bronze, silver, gold, mart, and report layers would all be keyed by \texttt{dataset\_id}. Dashboard queries and the report-pack notebook would then become parameterized so multiple retail datasets could coexist in one workspace. This would move RetailPulse closer to a reusable internal B2B analytics platform rather than a single-source demonstration.

Another future-work lane is predictive redesign. The current supervised models should remain outside the operational path until leakage-safe features, stricter train/test design, and model versioning are introduced. In the near term, the safer operational outputs are descriptive dashboards, recommendation tables, customer segments, and rule-based action files. Only after the canonical retail contract is stable should the predictive layer be promoted beyond exploratory insight.

\section*{9. Conclusion}
RetailPulse achieves the project goal it set for itself: it demonstrates a reproducible Databricks retail analytics system that is stronger than a notebook demo and more honest than a glossy but weakly evidenced report. The system ingests sampled Instacart data, builds a bronze-silver-gold Delta pipeline, exposes OLAP outputs, recommendation rules, customer segments, exploratory predictive metrics, streaming validation, and optimization evidence, and packages the results into both a Databricks AI/BI dashboard and a notebook fallback.

Just as importantly, the submission stays disciplined about what is not proven. It does not claim revenue analytics without price data. It does not claim calendar analytics without dates. It does not claim that the current supervised metrics are production-grade. That combination of implemented functionality and bounded claims makes RetailPulse a stronger and more credible project. The result is a reviewable, rerunnable, and presentation-ready analytics system that can also serve as the foundation for a more general self-service retail platform in later work.

